{"componentChunkName":"component---node-modules-gatsby-theme-code-notes-src-templates-note-js","path":"/management-tips/how_to_play_friendly_hardball_in_a_negotiation","result":{"data":{"mdx":{"body":"function _extends() { _extends = Object.assign || function (target) { for (var i = 1; i < arguments.length; i++) { var source = arguments[i]; for (var key in source) { if (Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(source, key)) { target[key] = source[key]; } } } return target; }; return _extends.apply(this, arguments); }\n\nfunction _objectWithoutProperties(source, excluded) { if (source == null) return {}; var target = _objectWithoutPropertiesLoose(source, excluded); var key, i; if (Object.getOwnPropertySymbols) { var sourceSymbolKeys = Object.getOwnPropertySymbols(source); for (i = 0; i < sourceSymbolKeys.length; i++) { key = sourceSymbolKeys[i]; if (excluded.indexOf(key) >= 0) continue; if (!Object.prototype.propertyIsEnumerable.call(source, key)) continue; target[key] = source[key]; } } return target; }\n\nfunction _objectWithoutPropertiesLoose(source, excluded) { if (source == null) return {}; var target = {}; var sourceKeys = Object.keys(source); var key, i; for (i = 0; i < sourceKeys.length; i++) { key = sourceKeys[i]; if (excluded.indexOf(key) >= 0) continue; target[key] = source[key]; } return target; }\n\n/* @jsxRuntime classic */\n\n/* @jsx mdx */\nvar _frontmatter = {\n  \"title\": \"How to Play “Friendly Hardball” in a Negotiation\",\n  \"emoji\": \"💡\",\n  \"tags\": [\"management\"],\n  \"link\": \"https://hbr.org/2020/06/how-to-play-friendly-hardball-in-a-negotiation\",\n  \"created\": \"2020-08-19T16:45:18.000Z\",\n  \"modified\": \"2021-03-04T20:22:23.000Z\"\n};\n\nvar makeShortcode = function makeShortcode(name) {\n  return function MDXDefaultShortcode(props) {\n    console.warn(\"Component \" + name + \" was not imported, exported, or provided by MDXProvider as global scope\");\n    return mdx(\"div\", props);\n  };\n};\n\nvar Highlight = makeShortcode(\"Highlight\");\nvar layoutProps = {\n  _frontmatter: _frontmatter\n};\nvar MDXLayout = \"wrapper\";\nreturn function MDXContent(_ref) {\n  var components = _ref.components,\n      props = _objectWithoutProperties(_ref, [\"components\"]);\n\n  return mdx(MDXLayout, _extends({}, layoutProps, props, {\n    components: components,\n    mdxType: \"MDXLayout\"\n  }), mdx(\"h2\", {\n    \"id\": \"tip\"\n  }, \"Tip\"), mdx(\"p\", null, \"In any negotiation, your goal is to get what you want while maintaining a good relationship with your counterpart. In reality, this can be a tough tightrope to walk.\"), mdx(\"p\", null, \"One technique that might help is to juxtapose what you can offer against the least your counterpart is willing to accept. In other words, you can ask something like, \\u201CHow does my offer compare to your minimum price?\\u201D This may seem counterintuitive, but it can encourage the other person to make a less ambitious counteroffer, because they are reminded of the price that they were willing to settle for.\"), mdx(\"p\", null, \"It\\u2019s important to \", mdx(Highlight, {\n    mdxType: \"Highlight\"\n  }, \"do your homework\"), \" ahead of time and figure out the \\u201Cbargaining zone,\\u201D or the area between your baseline expectations and your counterpart\\u2019s. If you make an offer without considering the bargaining zone, you\\u2019re unlikely to be successful, no matter how you frame that offer.\"), mdx(\"p\", null, \"Also, \", mdx(Highlight, {\n    mdxType: \"Highlight\"\n  }, \"do your best to determine whether there are any preexisting offers on the table that might impact your counterpart\\u2019s walkaway price\"), \", and adjust your strategy accordingly. If your counterpart has more attractive other offers, your walkaway framing is less likely to work.\"), mdx(\"p\", null, \"Before anchoring your counterparty, \", mdx(Highlight, {\n    mdxType: \"Highlight\"\n  }, \"determine whether the issue in question is truly isolated, or may have implications for other issues\"), \". A premature offer pertaining to a single issue, even one that\\u2019s in your favor, may hinder you from finding tradeoffs between issues that could create even more shared value.\"), mdx(\"p\", null, \"The walkaway-price framing technique will \", mdx(Highlight, {\n    mdxType: \"Highlight\"\n  }, \"be especially effective when your counterparty has either no alternatives, or only weak alternatives\"), \". It\\u2019s important to keep in mind that if your counterparty does have a strong alternative offer, the walkaway-price method could backfire. However, if you\\u2019re confident that your counterparty\\u2019s existing options are limited, this strategy can be a simple though counterintuitive way to \\u201Cplay hardball\\u201D in your negotiation while maintaining a positive business relationship.\"), mdx(\"h3\", {\n    \"id\": \"translations\"\n  }, \"Translations\"), mdx(\"details\", null, mdx(\"summary\", null, \"\\uD83C\\uDDE8\\uD83C\\uDDF3\")));\n}\n;\nMDXContent.isMDXComponent = true;","frontmatter":{"title":"How to Play “Friendly Hardball” in a Negotiation","tags":["management"],"emoji":"💡","link":"https://hbr.org/2020/06/how-to-play-friendly-hardball-in-a-negotiation","modified":"March 4, 2021","modifiedTimestamp":"2021-03-04T20:22:23.000Z"},"fields":{"slug":"/management-tips/how_to_play_friendly_hardball_in_a_negotiation"},"tableOfContents":{"items":[{"url":"#tip","title":"Tip","items":[{"url":"#translations","title":"Translations"}]}]},"parent":{"__typename":"File","relativePath":"management-tips/how_to_play_friendly_hardball_in_a_negotiation.mdx"}}},"pageContext":{"id":"30572c2b-e91d-57e7-87f5-f8a4b6b98ee5","previous":{"id":"2f311ad3-68d8-5e87-bcf2-dbf0d7eff619","frontmatter":{"title":"How to Respond When an Employee Cries at Work","tags":["management"]},"fields":{"slug":"/management-tips/how_to_respond_when_an_employee_cries_at_work"}},"next":{"id":"82521bb3-5da1-5724-8a40-86b051325227","frontmatter":{"title":"How